President Donald Trump of the United States and Chairman Kim Jong Un of North Korea held a historic summit in Singapore on June 12, 2018. They discussed establishing new US-North Korea relations and building a lasting peace regime on the Korean Peninsula. Trump committed to providing security guarantees to North Korea, while Kim reaffirmed his commitment to complete denuclearization. Both leaders recognized the significance of the summit and committed to implementing the joint statement fully and expeditiously. They also agreed to hold follow-up negotiations led by the US Secretary of State and a relevant high-level North Korean official. Trump and Kim pledged to cooperate for the development of new US-North Korea relations and for peace, prosperity, and security in the Korean Peninsula and the world.